def inspect_all(solver_):
    """
    Incpects the solving process of the solver using instances from all available datasets 
    """
    for tag, instance in zip(tags_wb, instances_wb):
        print(f'* {tag} *')
        solver_.solve(*instance)
        solver_.inspect()

Hyperparameters one by one¶

Inspection of SA solver's hyperparameters with fixed other values

In [19]:
N_PER_FILE = 20
STATISTICS_DEFAULT = ['n_solved', 'time_avg', 'err_avg']
In [20]:
def _collect_hyperparam_data(hyperparam_name, possible_values, kwargs=None, solver_class=WSATSolverSA):
    """
    Performs an experiment for different values of specified hyperparameter

    Other hyperparameters are fixed (either left as default or specified as kwargs parameter)
    """
    if kwargs is None:
        kwargs = {}
    
    solvers_dict = {f'{hyperparam_name}_{x}': solver_class(**{hyperparam_name: x}, **kwargs) for x in possible_values}
    return measure_multiple_solvers(solvers_dict, 
                                    gen_instances_easy_factory,
                                    gen_solutions_easy_factory,
                                    indices=DATA_TAGS_EASY, 
                                    limit=N_PER_FILE, 
                                    verbose=VERBOSE)

def _aggregate_dataframes(dfs_, columns=None):
    """
    Aggregates data from multiple dataframes (1 dataframe per solver) into 1 (1 row per solver)
    """
    if columns is None:
        columns = STATISTICS_DEFAULT
    df = pd.DataFrame()
    
    df['id'] = pd.Series(range(len(dfs_.keys())))
    df['solver'] = pd.Series(dfs_.keys())
    for col in columns:
        df[col] = pd.Series([df[col].mean() for tag, df in dfs_.items()])
        
    return df

def get_hyperparam_data(hyperparam_name, possible_values, solver_kwargs_fixed=None):
    """
    Either performs an experiment with focus on different hyperparameter values
    or loads the data from a CSV files.
    
    _collect_hyperparam_data wrapper which conducts it as an experiment (MultiExperiment)
    """
    path = f'{DIR_RESULTS}{hyperparam_name}/'
    tags = [f'{hyperparam_name}_{x}' for x in possible_values]
    mkdir_safe(path)

    experiment = MultiExperiment(tags=tags,
                                 paths=[f'{path}{tag}.csv' for tag in tags],
                                 f=_collect_hyperparam_data,
                                 kwargs={
                                     'hyperparam_name': hyperparam_name,
                                     'possible_values': possible_values,
                                     'kwargs': solver_kwargs_fixed
                                 })
    dfs = experiment_multi(experiment, allow_loading=LOAD_FROM_CSV, verbose=VERBOSE)
    # aggregate into one dataframe in the end
    return _aggregate_dataframes(dfs)

Plot function:

In [21]:
def plot_stats_default(data: pd.DataFrame, tags=None, figsize=(18, 5), categorical=False):
    """
    Plot all 3 default stats aggregated from experiments in separate subplots 
    """
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    c = '#1f77b4'
    if tags is None:
        try:
            tags = data['solver'].apply(lambda x: f'{x.split(".")[0][-1]}.{x.split(".")[1]}')
        except Exception:
            tags = list(range(data.shape[0]))
    plot_function, kwargs = (plt.bar, {'width': 0.5}) if categorical else (plt.plot, {})
            
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
    plot_function(tags, data['n_solved'], color=c, **kwargs)
    plt.title('number of solved instances')
    
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
    plot_function(tags, data['time_avg'], color=c, **kwargs)
    plt.title('average time (in ns)')
    
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
    plot_function(tags, data['err_avg'], color=c, **kwargs)
    plt.title('average error (relative)')
    
    plt.show()

Hyperparameters tuning via scikit-learn¶

Finding best hyperparameters setup by brute force using ParameterGrid from scikit-learn library

In [26]:
from sklearn.model_selection import ParameterGrid

grid_dict = {
    'start_acceptance_ratio': np.arange(0.8, 1.0, 0.05),
    'penalize_strategy': ['simple', 'weighted', 'greedy'],
    'weights_importance': np.arange(0.0, 0.5, 0.1),
    'cooling_coef': [0.999, 0.99, 0.95, 0.9],
}

hparams = ParameterGrid(grid_dict)

N_PER_FILE = 20

Definition of the search functions:

In [27]:
import time
import datetime

columns = ['id', 'solved', 'err_avg']

def _get_time_str():
    return f'{datetime.datetime.now():%H:%M}'

def _score_hyperparams(hparams_dict, solver_class=WSATSolverSA):
    """
    Tests hyperparams by solving instances accross all datasets 
    
    Returns a tuple: solved_ratio, avg_error
    
    solved_ratio: ratio of instances for which the solver was able to find a solution
    avg_error: relative error averaged accross successfully solved instances 
    """
    solver = solver_class(**hparams_dict)
    data_in = gen_instances_easy_factory.call(), gen_solutions_easy_factory.call()
    df = measure_solver(solver, *data_in, limit=N_PER_FILE)
    
    n_succes, n_instances = df['n_solved'].sum(), df['n_instances'].sum() 
    err_cum = sum([row['err_avg'] * row['n_solved'] for _, row in df.iterrows()])
    err_avg = 1 if n_succes == 0 else err_cum / n_succes 
    
    return n_succes / n_instances, err_avg

def _load_checkpoint(path):
    """
    Attempts to load a checkpoint from hparams tuning
    
    Returns a tuple (dataframe, index)
    
    dataframe: pd.DataFrame with loaded data
    index: initial index of hparams combination to continue with
    """
    df, start_idx = pd.DataFrame(columns=columns), 0
    # try to load a checkpoint
    try:
        df = pd.read_csv(checkpoint_path)
        start_idx = df.shape[0]
        assert start_idx == df['id'].max() + 1
        print(f'[Checkpoint load] Checkpoint succesfully loaded. Rows loaded: {start_idx}')
    except Exception:
        print('[Checkpoint load] Unable to load any hyperparameters checkpoint.')
    
    return df, start_idx
    

def tune_hparams(checkpoint_path, checkpoint_freq=10, verbose=VERBOSE):
    """
    Finds the best hyperparameters for WSATSolver
    
    Allows checkpoint saving as the whole process can take hours to complete 
    """
    n_total = len(hparams)
    if verbose:
        print(f'Tuning hyperparameters by brute force. Number of combinations {n_total}, Time: {_get_time_str()}')
        
    df, start_idx = _load_checkpoint(checkpoint_path)
    start = time.time()
    for i, kwargs in enumerate(hparams):
        # skip unnecessary rows
        if i < start_idx: 
            continue
        # collect stats
        result = _score_hyperparams(kwargs)
        row = pd.Series((i, *result), index=columns)
        df = df.append(row, ignore_index=True)
        # checkpoint
        if (i + 1) % checkpoint_freq == 0:
            df.to_csv(checkpoint_path, index=False)
            if verbose: 
                print(f'Saving checkpoint @ {checkpoint_path}. Number of row saved: {i + 1 - start_idx}')
                t = time.time() - start
                complete_total, complete_now = (i + 1) / n_total, (i + 1 - start_idx) / (n_total - start_idx)
                print(f'[{_get_time_str()}] {i + 1 - start_idx} ({i + 1}) complete '
                f'~ {complete_now * 100:.2f} % ({complete_total * 100:.2f} %). '
                f'Runtime: {t:.1f} s, end expected in {(t / (i + 1 - start_idx)  * (n_total - start_idx)) - t:.1f} s')
            
    if verbose:
        print(f'----------\nTuning complete. Time: {_get_time_str()}, duration: {t:.1f} s')
        print(f'Saving data @ {checkpoint_path}. Number of row saved: {n_total}')
    return df
